---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="How this site is verified"
  description="The evidence behind the site's accuracy: reference-implementation cross-checks, the official test vectors, and deterministic tests."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="7 · Reference"
    title="How this site is verified"
    lead="An explainer is only as good as its accuracy. This site's facts are checked against independent, mechanical evidence — not just careful reading."
  />

  <p>
    Reviewing prose against a specification can miss errors and invent false ones. So the technical
    content here is held to evidence that does not depend on anyone's judgement: a working reference
    receiver, the official test vectors, and deterministic tests.
  </p>

  <h2>Four pillars</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The official PDF is the authority.</strong> The Galileo OSNMA SIS ICD v1.1 and Receiver
      Guidelines v1.3 are the supreme reference — above any conversion or third-party code. Contested
      values were read directly from the official tables.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cross-checked against a reference implementation.</strong> Every value table and field
      layout was compared against <strong>OSNMAlib</strong>, the peer-reviewed KU Leuven OSNMA
      receiver. Every difference turned out to be a permissive OSNMAlib superset; the PDF confirmed
      this site.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Proven on the official test vectors.</strong> OSNMAlib was run on the EUSPA test
      vectors and reproduced <strong>all 19 scenarios exactly</strong> — independently confirming the
      field values, the cryptography, and the lifecycle status transitions described here (including
      every EOC / CREV / NPK / PKREV / NMT / OAM step).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Deterministic tests + a traceable ledger.</strong> A test suite enforces the bit-field
      sums, the value-table arithmetic, and — crucially — that <strong>every section this site cites
      actually exists in the official documents</strong>. A claims ledger backs each load-bearing
      statement with a verbatim quote.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The live demos use real data</h2>
  <p>
    The Merkle Tree Explorer recomputes the root from the genuine EUSPA test-vector key and matches the
    published root bit-for-bit; the same cryptographic helpers are checked against that real value in
    the test suite. Where conceptual clarity is better served by clean examples (the TESLA timeline,
    the chain-of-trust overview) the site says so.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security" title="An honest ceiling">
    <p>
      No automated process — and no language model — can <em>guarantee</em> zero error. What this
      programme guarantees is that mistakes are <strong>caught</strong>: a claim that isn't backed by a
      test, the reference implementation, or a real document quote doesn't survive. A short list of
      deliberate simplifications and the two items reserved for human-expert sign-off is kept in the
      project's verification notes.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <Callout type="note">
    <p>
      The verification artefacts (the reference cross-check, the test-vector run, the claims ledger and
      the scope notes) live in <code>docs/verification/</code> in the project repository, alongside a
      script that reproduces the 19/19 reference-implementation run.
    </p>
  </Callout>
</BaseLayout>
